---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SITE, GAME } from '../consts';

const faq = [
  { q: 'How do you fix the wand in Moonlight Peaks?', a: "Confirmed at launch: your wand starts broken and unusable. The fix happens automatically as part of the \"The Magic of Crops\" quest — Luna sends you to Sabrina at Webb of Wonders, but it's actually Noel who ends up fixing it, with duct tape. There's no separate item to buy or side-errand to run; finishing the quest chain fixes it." },
  { q: "Why hasn't my wand quest triggered yet?", a: 'Confirmed: "The Magic of Crops" is gated behind finishing "The Dinner Party" quest, then waiting 2 days and reading a letter from Luna. Community-reported: some guides place this trigger at the start of Summer, others describe it happening around two and a half weeks in — if your letter hasn\u2019t arrived, the most likely cause is simply that The Dinner Party or its follow-up wait period isn\u2019t finished yet, not a missed item or shop purchase.' },
  { q: 'What spells are confirmed?', a: "Confirmed at launch: Aquaflux (a self-pouring watering spell, required for magical crops), maturing crops faster, clearing rocks, summoning rain, and a Witches' Circle teleport spell. You cast by drawing a circle-and-dot pattern with the wand equipped, and spells cost mana. Community-reported: one source's in-game almanac count puts the full spell list at 12 total; not independently cross-verified here." },
  { q: 'What does the Alter Ego Elixir do?', a: 'The Alter Ego Elixir is a potion, sold by Sabrina at Webb of Wonders, that changes your appearance. It is one example of the many brews you can make through potion-making.' },
  { q: 'Is magic required to play?', a: 'Witchcraft is a core pillar of the game and makes farming and gathering easier, but Moonlight Peaks is a cozy life sim — you can play at your own pace.' },
];

const jsonLd = [
  { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: faq.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })) },
  { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'BreadcrumbList', itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: SITE.url },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Magic', item: new URL('/magic', SITE.url).href },
  ] },
];
---
<Base
  title="Moonlight Peaks Magic Guide: Fix the Wand, Moon Fruit & Mana Progression"
  description="How to fix the wand in Moonlight Peaks, why the Magic of Crops quest hasn't triggered, Moon Fruit, and how the Mana Extractor works — confirmed facts kept separate from community reports."
  path="/magic"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  crumbs={[{ label: 'Magic' }]}
  showExport
>
  <article class="page">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Entry · Magic</p>
      <h1>Moonlight Peaks <em>magic</em> guide</h1>
      <p class="intro">
        Witchcraft is one of the core pillars of {GAME.title}. Here's how spellcasting works, how
        to fix your wand, and what's confirmed versus community-reported about magic progression.
        Updated {SITE.updated}.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Quick answer:</strong> your wand starts broken. It gets fixed automatically as part
        of the "The Magic of Crops" quest, which unlocks after finishing "The Dinner Party" and
        waiting on a letter from Luna. Once fixed, spellcasting opens up — no separate purchase or
        side-errand needed.
      </div>

      <h2>How to fix the broken wand</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed at launch: your wand is inherited and broken from the start, unusable until a
        specific quest resolves it. Luna sends you a letter, and after visiting her you're pointed
        toward Sabrina at Webb of Wonders to get the wand repaired. Confirmed comedic twist: it's
        actually <strong>Noel</strong> who ends up fixing it, with duct tape, not Sabrina herself.
        There's no item to buy or extra step to hunt for — completing "The Magic of Crops" (below)
        fixes it as part of the story.
      </p>

      <h2>Why the wand quest hasn't triggered</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed: "The Magic of Crops" requires finishing <strong>The Dinner Party</strong> quest
        first, then waiting roughly 2 in-game days for a letter from Luna. <span class="tag-community">Community-reported</span> sources disagree slightly on the exact timing — one
        describes the letter arriving "around Night 18," another says it lines up with the start
        of Summer — so we're not treating either as the confirmed trigger day. If your letter
        hasn't shown up, the most likely explanation is that The Dinner Party (or its follow-up
        wait) simply isn't finished yet, not a missed shop item or side quest.
      </p>

      <h2>The Magic of Crops quest</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed: this quest is how spellcasting and your first magical crop both unlock at once.
        <span class="tag-community">Community-reported</span> step order (consistent across
        multiple launch-week guides, though not independently re-verified by us step-for-step):
        Luna's letter leads to a cutscene — sources vary on whether this happens at her farm or in
        the forest above your own home — where she shows you Moonfruit seeds and asks you to
        nurture them. Since your wand is broken, she sends you to get it fixed (see above). Once
        fixed, you water the Moonfruit with your new Aquaflux spell for a couple of nights, which
        completes the quest and unlocks spellcasting for the rest of the game.
      </p>

      <h2>How Moon Fruit fits into magic progression</h2>
      <p>
        <span class="tag-community">Community-reported</span> Moonfruit is a magical crop, shaped
        like a crescent moon, that can only be watered with the Aquaflux spell — a regular
        watering can doesn't work on it. It's the specific crop tied to unlocking spellcasting via
        "The Magic of Crops," and after that quest, Luna's shop expands to sell magical seeds more
        generally.
      </p>

      <h2>How casting works</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed at launch: equip your wand, then draw a circle-and-dot pattern, following the
        on-screen prompt with the D-pad (or your Joy-Con/mouse). Below your stamina bar you'll see a
        separate mana bar — you start with a small pool (3 points) and regain roughly one star per
        night's sleep, so managing mana across a night matters. A few rare foods and drinks restore
        mana early on.
      </p>

      <h2>How the Mana Extractor works</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed: the Mana Extractor is a craftable machine, unlocked through the "Building a
        Mana Extractor" quest, that produces <strong>Mana Essence</strong> from magical crops and
        herbs. Consuming Mana Essence (directly or added to food) restores mana faster than sleeping
        alone — a meaningful upgrade once magic seeds get expensive to keep watered with limited
        early mana.
      </p>

      <h2>Confirmed spell list</h2>
      <p>
        Confirmed spells taught by the town's witches: <strong>Aquaflux</strong>, a self-pouring
        watering can spell unlocked via "The Magic of Crops" (regular watering cans don't work on
        magical crops — they need Aquaflux); plus <strong>maturing crops</strong>
        faster, <strong>clearing rocks</strong>, <strong>summoning rain</strong>, and a
        <strong>Witches' Circle teleport</strong>. As you learn, you expand your repertoire further.
        Community-reported: a single casting of Aquaflux covers up to 16 crop tiles, so planning
        your magical-crop layout in blocks of 16 gets the most out of each cast.
      </p>
      <p>
        Community-reported: beyond the story-unlocked spells above, <a href="/characters/ludo">Ludo</a>'s
        shop separately sells wand-type tools — a pickaxe wand, the Aquaflux watering wand, and an
        Arborescent (tree-moving) wand — aimed at saving stamina on repetitive chores rather than
        combat or story progression.
      </p>

      <h2>Potions & the Alter Ego Elixir</h2>
      <p>
        Alongside spells, you brew potions to unlock all kinds of effects. The headline example is
        the <strong>Alter Ego Elixir</strong>, sold by Sabrina at Webb of Wonders, which changes your
        appearance. Potion-making is described as a key skill, so expect a range of brews with
        different uses across the game.
      </p>

      <h2>Common wand and magic progression problems</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wand still broken after visiting Sabrina:</strong> confirmed — she doesn't
          actually fix it herself. Keep progressing "The Magic of Crops"; Noel is the one who
          completes the repair.</li>
        <li><strong>No letter from Luna yet:</strong> confirm "The Dinner Party" is actually
          finished, then allow the reported ~2-day wait before assuming something's stuck.</li>
        <li><strong>Can't water Moonfruit with your regular watering can:</strong> expected —
          <span class="tag-community">community-reported</span> magical crops specifically require
          Aquaflux, not the standard can.</li>
        <li><strong>Running out of mana constantly:</strong> confirmed as a known early-game
          bottleneck — see <a href="/known-issues">known issues</a> for how reviewers described
          this, and prioritize the Mana Extractor and mana-restoring food once available.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Witchcraft & your vampire powers</h2>
      <p>
        Magic sits alongside your vampire abilities — including <a href="/shapeshifting">shapeshifting
        into a bat or your Hellkitten</a>. See the
        <a href="/beginner-guide">beginner guide</a> for how the supernatural side fits together,
        and <a href="/farming">farming</a> for how Aquaflux and magical crops connect to your plot.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        {faq.map((f) => (
          <details>
            <summary>{f.q}</summary>
            <p>{f.a}</p>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div class="callout wip">
        Related: <a href="/farming">farming & crops</a>, <a href="/character-creator">character creator</a>, <a href="/shapeshifting">shapeshifting</a>, <a href="/items">items</a>, <a href="/quests">quests</a>, <a href="/beginner-guide">beginner guide</a>.
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
  <style>
    .tag-community {
      display: inline-block; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.65rem; letter-spacing: 0.02em;
      color: var(--faint); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 999px; padding: 2px 8px;
      margin-right: 6px; vertical-align: middle;
    }
  </style>
</Base>
